Sure! Here's an example of how you can implement basic navigation in React Native using React Navigation library:

First, you will need to install the `react-navigation` package by running the following command:

```
npm install @react-navigation/native
```

Then, depending on the version of React Navigation you are using, install the required dependencies. For example, if you're using version 6.x, you can install the following packages:

```
npm install react-native-screens react-native-safe-area-context
```

Here's a basic example of creating a Stack Navigator:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import { NavigationContainer } from '@react-navigation/native';
import { createNativeStackNavigator } from '@react-navigation/native-stack';

// Import your screens
import HomeScreen from './HomeScreen';
import DetailsScreen from './DetailsScreen';

// Create a stack navigator
const Stack = createNativeStackNavigator();

function App() {
  return (
    <NavigationContainer>
      <Stack.Navigator>
        <Stack.Screen name="Home" component={HomeScreen} />
        <Stack.Screen name="Details" component={DetailsScreen} />
      </Stack.Navigator>
    </NavigationContainer>
  );
}

export default App;
```

In this example, we import the necessary components from the `@react-navigation/native` and `@react-navigation/native-stack` libraries. We create a `Stack.Navigator` component and define our screens using the `Stack.Screen` component.

Make sure you have created the `HomeScreen` and `DetailsScreen` components in separate files.

This is a basic example to get you started with navigation in React Native using React Navigation. You can further customize the navigation by adding more screens, configuring options, and using different navigators provided by React Navigation.

